Imagine a very long web page with many sections (such as a single-page HTML specification). If a user requests a specific part of it (such as page.html#section7), can the Web server first transmit that part and then transmit the others?
Stream Order:
1. The beginning of the HTML document, up to the <body> tag
2. The HTML code for section 7
3. The HTML code for sections 1, 2, 3, etc.
The browser must ensure that sections 1 through 6 are inserted above section 7 of the web page.
Would that be reasonable? Would it be useful?
The goal I want to achieve is to have the linked section (#section7) rendered as quickly as possible without reimplementing it using JavaScript or similar technologies. I want a very long HTML document, but the linked sections should still be rendered as quickly as possible. This can be achieved with just HTML.
Content can be streamed in this way, and the browser will insert each <contents> element into the corresponding <div> element.
<div id=sec1></div>
<div id=sec2></div>
And so on.
<div id=sec7>section 7…</div>
<contents for=sec1>section 1…</contents>
<contents for=sec2>section 2…</contents>
etc.
Although the streaming order is out of sequence, the browser will assemble the HTML document in order.
@user22 Actually, it's possible to reorder document content without using JS. However, if you want the server to do something, you can't use the URL hash part anymore; instead, you should use query string parameters to let the server know which section you want to view first. As for reordering page content, you have the following options:
1. Use CSS
2. Use templates with slots
@user23 That's right. The issue is that the visual order (what the user sees) doesn't match the DOM order. If HTML could support out-of-order streaming while the browser arranges the content in order within the DOM, it might be very useful.
However, the slot method seems quite promising. I'll give it a try.
@user22 Oh, are you wanting the browser to automatically correct the DOM order?
@user23 That's exactly what I was thinking. The only reason for transmitting section 7 first is so that the user can see it as quickly as possible. It would be great if this could be achieved without affecting the DOM order, allowing the browser to ensure that the final DOM order matches the visual order.
In other words, transmit section 7 first, but the final result (DOM and visual appearance) should be exactly the same as if all sections were transmitted in order.
@user22 @user33 You can check out PHOOOS without using JS: https://github.com/niutech/phooos
